{
  "version": 2,
  "name": "ApricotBloom",
  "description": "Scene 3 (scene ladder flagship, WIP) - a single scanned apricot sprig growing up out of its own stem, macro. One material cluster of cc0__japanese_apricot_prunus_mume.glb (cluster card 1..3 picks which; fit=unit_box + recenter so the sprig is normalized at origin) grows via a two-part front driven by one growPhase card: (1) reveal - node.taper_mesh axis Y, taper=0, razor-thin length 0.05, so geometry above the front collapses to zero-area triangles (invisible; a wide feather showed collapsing petals as smeared tents, measured 2026-07-11); (2) unfurl - node.bend_mesh nod whose center is hinged just below the front (droop_hinge scale_offset) and whose weights are a node.mesh_ramp curl mask LAGGING the front by 0.25 normalized (curl_phase), so freshly revealed growth arrives nodding over and straightens as the front passes - the fern-frond gesture at sprig scale (bend 0.28 rad; 1.0 rad about the base read as a scythe, and push_along_normals deflate inverted the thin twig shell - both falsified by render). Killed candidates for the growth character: global-axis twist (lateral petal shear at partial phases), normals-deflate (photogrammetry shells self-intersect). Known residual: petals straddling the front smear briefly mid-collapse (per-vertex front vs rigid petal features - judge in motion). growPhase 0 = bare, 1 = fully grown.",
